# Build Brief — "Sluice" (working name)
### The settlement layer for the agent-paid web
*Lepton Agents Hackathon · Canteen × Circle × Arc · Jun 15 → Jun 29, 2026*

> **Name is not final.** This brief uses **Sluice** throughout as a placeholder. Once you pick from the top-10 list, find-replace `Sluice` everywhere.
>
> **One-line pitch:** *Any unit of value on the web — a read, a second, a citation, a listen, a call — made payable by humans and machines, metered and settled on Arc in USDC. Creators get paid per use. Agents pay per use, and decide for themselves.*

---

## 0. Why this wins (the thesis in one page)

Three facts, all verified against the live 2026 landscape:

1. **The round leans to creators (RFB 6).** The hosts repeat one idea everywhere: *the hard part was never the rail, it was finding the people — and for creators, they're already gathered.* Traction is 30% of the score. The Distribution + Prior Art sections are a literal list of open-source communities (Ghost, Navidrome, Owncast, PeerTube, RSSHub, Mastodon, immich) that already have audiences and expose webhooks/APIs. **We attach nanopayments to one of them → real usage in days, not a faked demo.**

2. **There is a real, unbuilt primitive — the "Gas Observatory" of this hackathon.** x402 is a single-shot *request→pay→response* loop. Cloudflare itself says agents/crawlers need *deferred settlement* and *a single aggregated payment*. The hosts flag that *streaming payments are a real code gap in x402* and that the ERC-8004 reputation lane is nearly empty. **Nobody has packaged the metering + deferred-batch-settlement + streaming-rate primitive on Arc.** Gateway batches payments; the *meter that decides what/when to accrue and settle* is application work no one shipped.

3. **The hero use case is the biggest live fight in tech.** "AI pays to read you" is real: Cloudflare Pay Per Crawl (1B+ 402s/day pre-GA), RSL 1.0 backed by 1,500+ orgs, ClaudeBot's 38,065:1 crawl-to-refer ratio. The gap: RSL has no enforcement; Cloudflare needs you to be its customer. **Small creators and self-hosted communities have no open way to actually collect.** Circle lists "per crawl" as a nanopayments use case. The rail exists; the creator-owned toll booth does not.

**Sluice is that toll booth + the meter underneath it + an agent on each side that decides.** It hits all six RFBs, leans into RFB 6, and maxes all four scoring axes.

